You can ship Angular apps for three years and still not actually understand Angular.
I know because I did exactly that.
I knew the syntax. I knew the decorators. I could build a CRUD screen in my sleep. Then one production incident, one memory graph, one dependency injection bug that made no sense on paper, and I realized I had been driving the car without ever opening the hood.
This article is the hood.
Five concepts. Each one quietly running under almost every Angular app in production. Each one misunderstood by nearly everyone who uses it daily. Stay with me, because by the end you will look at your own codebase differently.
1. Trackby Is Not Optional, It Is a Performance Contract
The problem
Loops without a tracking function look completely fine until your list gets real.
@Component({
selector: 'task-list',
template: `<div *ngFor="let task of tasks">{{ task.title }}</div>`
})
export class TaskListComponent {
tasks: Task[] = [];
}Every time tasks gets a new array reference, even if only one item changed, Angular has no way to know which DOM nodes still match which data. So it throws away…
